observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
instruct the Municipal Accountant, the Municipal Budget Officer, the General Services Officer, and the Municipal Engineer to install the necessary internal controls to ensure that PPE additions are properly recorded in the General Journal upon delivery or completion in compliance with Section 122 of the Manual;
instruct the Municipal Engineer to identify whether or not each of the improvements/rehabilitations totaling ₱123,577,797.47 actually resulted in the replacement or destruction of parts of existing assets, and submit to the Audit Team a written report on the results of the identification, including a copy of the POW and breakdown of the cost of improvements/ rehabilitations, for further evaluation;
for rehabilitation assets identified to have replaced parts, instruct the Municipal Engineer to determine the total cost of the assets/parts replaced and submit a summary of such to the Municipal Accountant; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to compute the proportionate accumulated depreciation and carrying amount of all assets/parts replaced and prepare Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) to derecognize the carrying amounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to recompute the depreciation expenses for CY 2024 and accumulated depreciation balances as of January 1, 2024 and 2025, and make JEVs to reflect the accurate balances, taking into consideration the following:
ensure that depreciation commences on the date of delivery, in case of equipment, and on the date of project completion, in case of infrastructure assets, and in accordance with PAG for IPSAS 17;
ensure that road components are disaggregated and depreciated separately, and that the road lot component is not subjected to depreciation pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-008;
ensure that the estimated useful life to be used in the computation complies with Annex A of COA Circular No. 2003-007; and
ensure that the costs of asset improvements and rehabilitations are not provided with stand-alone provisions for depreciation, are added to the respective PPELCs of the pre-existing asset to determine the revised total cost of these specific assets, and that the revised total cost is duly reflected in the Lapsing Schedule for proper computation of depreciation over the remaining useful life of the asset.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
identify the status of the right-of-way of all local roads recorded in the books, whether such was donated to the Municipality of Moalboal, to component barangays, through usufruct, or otherwise;
for road right-of-way acquired in the name of the Municipality of Moalboal via donation, secure the Deeds of Donation of the lots concerned, determine the fair value of the lots at the date of donation, and prepare JEVs to record the road lot component as a debit to the Road Networks account and a credit to income or Government Equity;
for road right-of-way acquired in the name of the Municipality of Moalboal via donation, expedite the registration of these lands in the name of the Municipality of Moalboal under the Torrens Title System;
for road right-of-way acquired by the component barangays via donation, propose with the component barangays to donate the lot components concerned to the Municipality of Moalboal; otherwise, instruct the Municipal Accountant to initiate the recording of the road lot component in the barangay books at fair value at the date of acquisition, and transfer of the recorded road network assets in the books of the component barangays concerned;
for road lot components without road right-of-way documents, either exert efforts towards the retrieval of documents and records for further action thereof, or initiate efforts in the acquisition thereof;
instruct the Municipal Treasurer to expedite the preparation and/or maintenance of the Report on Local Road Networks and Local Road Network Ledger Cards for each local road in the formats as prescribed in Annex A and E of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to expedite the preparation and maintenance of the Local Road Network Ledger Cards for each local road in the format as prescribed in Annex D of the Circular, ensuring accuracy and completeness of the data to be supplied.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
expedite the registration of 18 parcels of land in the name of the Municipality of Moalboal under the Torrens Title System;
conduct a thorough records/documents tracing, as far as practicable, on the 15 parcels of land recorded in the Land account totaling ₱1,636,133.83 with the end view of providing a more reliable and accurate assignment of values for each parcel, and revising the ledgers and other records, if necessary;
exert efforts towards the retrieval of documents and records, either from the Municipality or from other agencies such as the Registry of Deeds, among others, on the reclaimed land, and submit a copy thereof to the Audit Team for further evaluation. Also, confer with the PRA to be properly guided with the next courses of action regarding the reclaimed land with the end in view of avoiding forfeiture thereof; and
disclose in the Notes to the Financial Statements the necessary facts on the subject reclaimed land, including the total land area of the land and the detailed breakdown of all infrastructure assets and buildings and other structures erected therein.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare a JEV to record the fund transfers without specific purpose totaling ₱350,000.00, following the proposed adjusting journal entry:
expedite the implementation and utilization of fund transfers totaling ₱6,450,000.00 in accordance with their intended purpose. Ensure that realignments for these fund transfers are approved by the Source Agency prior to implementation/utilization;
for dormant excess fund transfers totaling ₱1,587,305.54, exert efforts in the retrieval of their source documents and determine whether such excesses were dormant and expedite the application for write-off of these accounts in accordance with Circular No. 2023-008;
for other excess fund transfers, request authority from the SAs for the use of these funds; otherwise, return such funds to the SAs concerned. Ensure that the excess funds written off or authorized to be used for another purpose are properly authorized for use by Management through the enactment of supplemental budgets; and
instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that subsidy income is only recognized upon completion or fulfillment of the funds transferred with specific purpose. A separate monitoring shall be made by the Municipal Accountant for the purpose of monitoring actual fund utilization per fund transfer, akin to the subsidiary ledgers currently maintained for the Due to LGUs and Due to NGAs accounts.

We recommended and Management agreed to initiate steps in ascertaining that the obligations accompanying the long-outstanding AP are valid and existing; otherwise, cause the reversion to the unappropriated surplus in accordance with PD No. 1445.
We also recommended and Management agreed to initiate the implementation of COA Circular No. 2021-006, especially in signing contracts with distant suppliers. Ensure that the following are submitted to the Audit Team in accordance with Item IV.B.5 of the Circular prior to implementation for monitoring and evaluation:
duly signed Management Representation Letter using electronic documents in the format as prescribed in Annex A thereof;
designation of a focal person for all matters pertaining to electronic signing implementation of the government entity;
proof of development of a system documentation to be used for creating electronic records with signatures;
duly approved standard operating procedures developed for the creation, utilization, storage, security, and management of electronic records that contain signatures, to ensure that the records are protected from unauthorized alteration or destruction;
duly approved policy and guidelines developed regarding the scope of employee’s authority to use signatures on electronic documents, security measures for the protection of digital certificates, if any, and sanctions for misuse or abuse of signatures.

We recommended and Management agreed to initiate steps towards the revision of the Plantilla of personnel taking into consideration the additional manpower needs of all departments and offices of the Municipality, and taking consideration the following:
filling-in of vacancies in the Plantilla, especially the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator position;
assessing the eligibility, qualifications, and performance of existing JOs with the end in view of appointing them to regular Plantilla positions;
creating the required divisions in the MTO, such as the Cash Division, Revenue Division, Administrative Section, IT Unit, and Supplies and Property Division/Unit;
matching of position titles and actual responsibilities of certain personnel involved in the MTO, such as filling in vacant revenue collector positions or creating new positions for these personnel in accordance with the revised 2017 ORAOHRA;
creating and filling in the noted lacking mandatory positions of the Municipal Assessor’s Office in compliance with RA No. 7160 and the MRPAAO; and
creating and filling-in the noted lacking statutory positions of the MDRRMO in compliance with RA No. 10121 and NDRRMC-DILG-DBM-CSC JMC No. 2014-1.
